Designer Bharat Grover felt that Dheeraj Singh, 23, hadn't been dressing his age. So, the youngster was given a white shirt with a colourful panel on the button line, teamed with beige trousers. His hair was cut and styled into spikes. "I am very happy with my new look. Thank you HT City," said Dheeraj after his makeover.

Designer Anushree Jain gave a very unconvinced  Tarun Dhiman,27, a light blue formal shirt, and black trousers, teamed with a black belt. Tarun's spiked hair was tamed with gel, he was (almost forcibly) given a shave and was made to take off all the junk jewellery he wore. When the makeover was complete, Tarun said "I never imagined that I could look so good in a formal look. And my family is going to be delighted to see me look this civilized."

Meet HT City readers who won a style makeover, and were also gifted

Starting today, HT City is on a mission. We have brought together 60 stylists, fashion gurus, bloggers and fashion-forward celebs to help Delhi get rid of repeated fashion offences, dreadful styling and basic fashion crimes. Don't be a victim of delusional wardrobe choices and sartorial faux pas.  If you have any fashion queries, our experts will answer them. We have more in store too, with fun fashion workshops lined up. Mail us your pictures/ questions on htcity@hindustantimes.com, and become a part of our Style in the City campaign.  To make it more interesting, the usually stylish HT City team got together and sportingly 'unfashioned' itself to portray 11 characters that possess the fashion characteristics of typical style offenders in the city. As a part of the campaign, we will dissect, discuss and address each of these characters and give you their antidotes. So join us and help re-instate the city as the Fashion Capital of the country, and remember our fashion police is on the prowl, so be on your most stylish behaviour! #htcity

Today Hindustan Times printed over ten lakh textbooks along with the newspaper. Each copy of the newspaper in the Delhi-NCR region carried with it a textbook which can be cut out and shared with an underprivileged child. Do hand over the textbook within your copy of the HT to someone you know and care for - could be the maid's daughter, or that street-corner boy. And do share with us some story of that giving. 
But also, your support in this initiative is invaluable. In helping share this story on Facebook and on Twitter, and in helping the movement grow. #htcity #youreadtheylearn #ht
